01:03:29,535 --> 01:03:31,454
75!

635
01:03:45,635 --> 01:03:47,762
I remember when we first met.

636
01:03:48,638 --> 01:03:52,308
<i>I gave the most awful performance in
Way of The World.</i>

637
01:03:53,184 --> 01:03:58,397
I went to my dressing room and there
were the beautiful flowers you'd sent me.

638
01:03:58,522 --> 01:04:00,608
And then you walked in.

639
01:04:01,192 --> 01:04:02,651
- Flowers?
- Mm.

640
01:04:02,735 --> 01:04:05,488
Dozens of them. They were wonderful.

641
01:04:05,738 --> 01:04:08,949
I didn't send any.
Must have been someone else.

642
01:04:09,033 --> 01:04:11,243
I walked in and you thanked me.

643
01:04:12,077 --> 01:04:14,163
You're teasing me.

644
01:04:14,288 --> 01:04:17,041
Bloody waste of good money, flowers.

645
01:04:19,126 --> 01:04:21,212
- You didn't?
- No.

646
01:04:26,842 --> 01:04:28,927
Really?

647
01:04:33,182 --> 01:04:35,267
Really?

648
01:04:36,018 --> 01:04:39,146
I had them at a good price.
I robbed a grave.

649
01:04:43,442 --> 01:04:45,944
All you ever think about is money.

650
01:04:47,029 --> 01:04:49,865
All anyone ever thinks about is money.

651
01:05:11,053 --> 01:05:13,138
<i>(rustling)</i>

652
01:05:14,389 --> 01:05:16,141
Don't turn.

653
01:05:16,224 --> 01:05:18,268
- Mr Simms, is it?
- That's right.

654
01:05:18,351 --> 01:05:21,480
- You came alone?
- Yes, as you instructed.

655
01:05:21,688 --> 01:05:24,983
- Everything the same on the railway line?
- All the same.

656
01:05:25,066 --> 01:05:26,526
Then it'll be tomorrow.

657
01:05:26,610 --> 01:05:30,530
- What'll be tomorrow?
- Never you mind. Here's 100 quid for you.

658
01:05:30,780 --> 01:05:33,283
Look the other way and shut your mouth.

659
01:05:33,366 --> 01:05:35,952
- Right?
- Right, sir.

660
01:05:36,036 --> 01:05:38,622
Now, off you go and don't look back.

661
01:05:47,172 --> 01:05:49,299
<i>(snarling)</i>

662
01:05:49,716 --> 01:05:52,677
Get a bowl of water in there.

663
01:05:54,471 --> 01:05:56,681
Put it in the corner, over there.

664
01:05:56,765 --> 01:05:58,975
As far away from me as you can.

665
01:05:59,058 --> 01:06:02,312
- He's pretty heavy, ain't he?
- Pretty hungry too.

666
01:06:06,024 --> 01:06:08,776
Sorry, sir.
No one's allowed to ride in the van.

667
01:06:08,860 --> 01:06:12,280
I've got to accompany the animal.
It's very valuable.

668
01:06:12,363 --> 01:06:14,449
<i>(screech)</i>

669
01:06:16,242 --> 01:06:18,620
He gets upset if I'm not with him.

670
01:06:18,953 --> 01:06:21,039
Yeah, very well.

671
01:06:32,842 --> 01:06:34,927
Doesn't care for travel.

672
01:06:41,726 --> 01:06:44,353
- You mean it's to be you?
- Aye.

673
01:06:47,732 --> 01:06:52,028
Where'd you make them impressions?
They keep all them keys separate.

674
01:06:52,111 --> 01:06:54,196
- Do they?
- Aye, they do.

675
01:06:54,780 --> 01:06:56,866
How'd you pull 'em?

676
01:06:58,534 --> 01:07:00,619
With incredible skill.

677
01:07:26,437 --> 01:07:30,608
The next gold shipment is in a week.
This time we take it.

678
01:07:31,108 --> 01:07:34,737
Agar will replace the gold
with these lead bars...

679
01:07:34,820 --> 01:07:37,573
..and throw the bags
from the train at Romney,...

680
01:07:37,656 --> 01:07:41,910
..where Barlow will collect them
and then drive to Folkestone.

681
01:07:41,994 --> 01:07:43,454
<i>Where will we be?</i>

682
01:07:43,537 --> 01:07:47,458
In a first-class compartment
enjoying the journey.

683
01:07:47,958 --> 01:07:50,043
What happens afterward?

684
01:07:50,127 --> 01:07:52,254
We divide the gold as agreed.

685
01:07:52,629 --> 01:07:54,715
After that.

686
01:07:55,048 --> 01:07:58,427
- After that?
- Yes, after that!

687
01:08:04,016 --> 01:08:06,101
You and I will go to Paris.

688
01:08:17,070 --> 01:08:21,324
You have it all worked out.
We ride on the train and they do the work.

689
01:08:21,408 --> 01:08:24,953
They have to earn their share, don't they?

690
01:08:25,078 --> 01:08:27,164
It's all very smooth.

691
01:08:28,748 --> 01:08:30,959
Unless something goes wrong.

692
01:08:31,668 --> 01:08:33,378
What could go wrong?

693
01:08:33,795 --> 01:08:35,881
My dear Mr Simms.

694
01:08:36,173 --> 01:08:38,300
As your humble servant,...

695
01:08:39,217 --> 01:08:42,596
..I would be greatly obliged
and indebted...

696
01:08:43,722 --> 01:08:48,435
..if you could contrive to meet with me
at the Palace, Sydenham...

697
01:08:49,227 --> 01:08:51,313
..for the purpose...

698
01:08:52,897 --> 01:08:54,983
For the purpose...

699
01:08:55,900 --> 01:08:59,529
For the purpose
of discussing some matters of...

700
01:08:59,696 --> 01:09:01,698
..mutual interest.

701
01:09:01,781 --> 01:09:03,867
Most respectfully,...

702
01:09:04,367 --> 01:09:06,578
..William Williams, Esquire.

703
01:09:07,787 --> 01:09:09,873
That should do it.

704
01:09:11,749 --> 01:09:13,835
Well now, Willy...

705
01:09:14,419 --> 01:09:16,796
What's this fellow Simms up to, eh?

706
01:09:16,880 --> 01:09:19,090
Please, sir, I can't tell you.

707
01:09:19,215 --> 01:09:23,136
Should have thought of that before
we caught you with this purse.

708
01:09:23,428 --> 01:09:25,930
I don't want to go back to prison, sir.

709
01:09:26,014 --> 01:09:28,099
Well, then. Better tell us.

710
01:09:28,975 --> 01:09:30,810
I don't know, sir. I told you.

711
01:09:31,561 --> 01:09:35,606
All's I know is that he's a cracksman
planning a flash pull, he is.

712
01:09:35,690 --> 01:09:37,775
The letter will put you on to him.

713
01:09:43,531 --> 01:09:45,324
We'll see.

714
01:09:45,700 --> 01:09:47,785
They'll kill me, they will.

715
01:09:48,744 --> 01:09:51,873
Then see you aren't
running off again, eh?

716
01:09:54,584 --> 01:09:57,878
We'll have a look
at this mysterious Mr Simms.

717
01:10:06,429 --> 01:10:08,514
<i>(band plays)</i>

718
01:10:41,130 --> 01:10:43,090
Don't turn round, Willy.

719
01:10:48,846 --> 01:10:52,349
- Now, what is it?
- I'm needing a bit, Mr Simms.

720
01:10:53,767 --> 01:10:57,479
- You've been paid.
- I'm needing more.

721
01:10:58,647 --> 01:11:02,651
- You been working, Willy?
- No!

722
01:11:02,734 --> 01:11:05,654
- Did the crushers pick you up?
- I swear it, no!

723
01:11:10,951 --> 01:11:14,705
- Willy, if you've turned nose on me...
- I swear it's no flam.

724
01:11:14,788 --> 01:11:18,917
A finny or two's what I need
and that'll be an end to it.

725
01:11:20,877 --> 01:11:23,171
There's a finny in your pocket.

726
01:11:24,715 --> 01:11:26,675
You're sweating.

727
01:11:26,758 --> 01:11:30,512
If you've turned nose on me,
I'll see you in lavender.

728
01:11:30,595 --> 01:11:32,514
Not me, sir. I swear!

729
01:11:38,812 --> 01:11:40,897
Three crushers.

730
01:12:01,126 --> 01:12:03,211
Edward! Edward Pierce!

731
01:12:04,421 --> 01:12:08,174
Edward, we were wondering
what had become of you.

732
01:12:08,258 --> 01:12:10,343
I got married.

733
01:12:11,052 --> 01:12:13,138
Must dash.

734
01:12:16,808 --> 01:12:21,396
- Do you think he's in trouble?
- Wouldn't surprise me.

735
01:12:21,479 --> 01:12:25,733
Very rough man. Not a good sort at all.

736
01:13:48,440 --> 01:13:50,526
<i>(snoring)</i>

737
01:14:47,833 --> 01:14:49,918
<i>(thudding upstairs)</i>

738
01:15:55,233 --> 01:15:59,028
- So, the snakesman is dead.
- I'm afraid so, sir.

739
01:15:59,111 --> 01:16:03,282
- And this fellow Simms has vanished?
- Yes, sir.

740
01:16:03,366 --> 01:16:06,118
And we don't know who he is
or what he intends?

741
01:16:06,202 --> 01:16:09,372
- We are entirely without clues.
- No, not entirely.

742
01:16:09,455 --> 01:16:15,211
We know Simms arranged for Clean Willy
to break from Newgate some months ago.

743
01:16:15,294 --> 01:16:18,881
- So it's a long-standing plan.
- A plan we don't know.

744
01:16:18,964 --> 01:16:22,885
Quite. But we do know Simms is
a safecracker. He must be after safes.

745
01:16:22,968 --> 01:16:27,890
And Willy broke into the dispatcher's
office of the South Eastern Railway Line.

746
01:16:27,973 --> 01:16:30,059
Hmm.

747
01:16:30,392 --> 01:16:35,564
And it occurred to me, could this Simms
be planning to steal the Crimean gold?

748
01:16:35,648 --> 01:16:37,942
Steal from a moving railway train?

749
01:16:39,026 --> 01:16:41,195
Who could imagine such a thing?

750
01:16:41,278 --> 01:16:43,572
The next gold shipment is tomorrow.

751
01:16:43,656 --> 01:16:47,493
I've alerted the railway line
to take extra precautions.

752
01:16:47,576 --> 01:16:50,829
- What's this?
- Precautions, sir.

753
01:16:50,913 --> 01:16:55,250
I will ride the train to Folkestone tonight.
I shall be there tomorrow...

754
01:16:55,334 --> 01:16:58,504
..in case there's any tomfoolery
when the gold arrives.

755
01:16:58,587 --> 01:17:01,882
- Very enterprising of you.
- Thank you, sir.

756
01:17:02,383 --> 01:17:06,053
We've made new security
arrangements throughout.

757
01:17:06,136 --> 01:17:07,638
New lock.

758
01:17:07,721 --> 01:17:13,227
New guard, just in case they do have
the audacity to try for the Crimean gold.

759
01:17:13,310 --> 01:17:15,521
Excellent foresight, Mr Sharp.

760
01:17:15,604 --> 01:17:19,107
I must commend you
on your attention in this matter.

761
01:17:19,191 --> 01:17:22,569
We certainly wouldn't
want to lose that gold.

762
01:17:38,585 --> 01:17:42,964
It's all changed. Everything.
Everything's changed.

763
01:17:43,048 --> 01:17:47,344
No one's allowed to ride in the luggage
van save Burgess himself as guard.

764
01:17:47,427 --> 01:17:50,180
And they've got a new jack
on the platform...

765
01:17:50,263 --> 01:17:53,266
..who opens all parcels
large enough for a man to hide in.

766
01:17:53,350 --> 01:17:58,855
And if that ain't bad enough, they've gone
and fitted a lock on the luggage van door.

767
01:17:58,939 --> 01:18:05,111
They're locking it at the station and not
opening it until it gets to Folkestone.

768
01:18:05,195 --> 01:18:08,823
A precautionary measure.
All on account of the gold.

769
01:18:09,783 --> 01:18:12,952
Bloody outside lock!
It can't be worked from within.

770
01:18:13,036 --> 01:18:16,206
Even if I was to be able to
get inside the van...

771
01:18:16,289 --> 01:18:20,168
..I'd be locked inside there
until it gets into Folkestone.

772
01:18:20,251 --> 01:18:25,381
And who do you think's behind all this?
Only the crushers theirselves, that's who.

773
01:18:25,965 --> 01:18:28,134
Two plainclothes jacks were there...

774
01:18:28,218 --> 01:18:32,639
..saying as how a Mr Simms
was planning to rob the Crimean gold.

775
01:18:32,722 --> 01:18:37,310
They don't have a high opinion of your
intelligence. But they credit your nerve.

776
01:18:37,393 --> 01:18:42,565
And they've put crushers on every station
on the line and at Folkestone.

777
01:18:42,649 --> 01:18:44,901
So. Here we are.

778
01:18:47,612 --> 01:18:52,200
Burgess is no use. I can't get into the van
because of that jack opening everything.

779
01:18:52,283 --> 01:18:57,747
Even if I could, I couldn't get the gold out
as the door's locked from the outside.

780
01:18:57,830 --> 01:19:00,708
So what's it to have four keys, I ask you?

781
01:19:00,792 --> 01:19:04,879
Four keys or 40 keys -
it don't make no bloody difference!

782
01:19:04,962 --> 01:19:08,966
It's a waste, the whole thing!
And nothing to be done about it.

783
01:19:09,050 --> 01:19:12,929
All on account of they found you out,
Mr Edward bloody Simms Pierce!

784
01:19:13,012 --> 01:19:17,600
That was something you didn't think of.
What have you got to say about that?

785
01:19:23,314 --> 01:19:25,399
Find me a dead cat.

786
01:19:41,040 --> 01:19:43,125
<i>(sobbing)</i>

787
01:19:57,598 --> 01:19:59,892
Now then, missy, now then.

788
01:19:59,975 --> 01:20:02,770
Oh, please, sir, can you help me?

789
01:20:02,853 --> 01:20:05,314
The man is a heartless beast, he is.

790
01:20:05,773 --> 01:20:08,567
- What man?
- That guard upon the line, sir.

791
01:20:09,026 --> 01:20:12,446
He will not let me
set my dear brother on the train.

792
01:20:13,739 --> 01:20:16,116
He says it must be...

793
01:20:16,492 --> 01:20:18,035
..opened!

794
01:20:18,118 --> 01:20:21,288
Why... the cruel rogue.

795
01:20:21,371 --> 01:20:23,790
We'll have your brother on the train.

796
01:20:26,668 --> 01:20:28,212
There's, um...

797
01:20:28,295 --> 01:20:30,380
..no need to open it.

798
01:20:34,968 --> 01:20:38,347
I, um...
I see you have a Bateson's belfry here.

799
01:20:38,764 --> 01:20:40,557
Oh, yes, sir.

800
01:20:40,932 --> 01:20:46,897
Me brother, he was terrible afraid of being
buried alive, so here's the safety.

801
01:20:48,398 --> 01:20:52,986
Very thoughtful, I'm sure.
Just you dry your eyes. All will be well.

802
01:20:54,237 --> 01:20:56,323
Thank you, sir.

803
01:20:56,615 --> 01:20:59,451
I'll just... get this business finished.

804
01:21:04,372 --> 01:21:08,251
- How could you be so cruel?
- I only told her the new rules.

805
01:21:08,335 --> 01:21:12,047
- All containers to be opened.
- Yes, I know.

806
01:21:12,797 --> 01:21:17,260
Do you smell it? I think in this case
we can make an exception.

807
01:21:17,761 --> 01:21:18,970
Whatever you say.

808
01:21:19,054 --> 01:21:20,847
- Nephew!
- Uncle.

809
01:21:20,930 --> 01:21:22,432
Nephew,...

810
01:21:22,515 --> 01:21:27,312
..mind your duties. Open every parcel
and make no exception. No exception.

811
01:21:27,395 --> 01:21:29,856
<i>- Yes, Uncle.
- (sniffs)</i>

812
01:21:30,607 --> 01:21:33,943
- What's that ungodly stink?
- The, er...

813
01:21:37,530 --> 01:21:41,242
- Scheduled for the morning train?
- Yes, Uncle.

814
01:21:43,661 --> 01:21:46,706
- See that you open it.
- But, er... Uncle...

815
01:21:48,708 --> 01:21:50,793
No stomach for it, eh?

816
01:21:51,628 --> 01:21:54,005
Dear God, you're a delicate one.

817
01:21:54,922 --> 01:21:57,050
All right, I'll do it myself.

818
01:21:57,133 --> 01:21:59,218
For opened it must be.

819
01:22:02,180 --> 01:22:03,973
Oh! Oh!

820
01:22:04,056 --> 01:22:07,727
My dear brother!
Oh, Richard. Richard, he lives!

821
01:22:07,810 --> 01:22:09,896
He lives! Oh, he's alive!

822
01:22:10,188 --> 01:22:13,900
Oh, make haste. He's alive!
Oh, praise God, he's alive!

823
01:22:13,983 --> 01:22:15,610
Oh, he's alive!

824
01:22:15,693 --> 01:22:18,029
Hurry! Hurry! Lest we are too late.

825
01:22:18,112 --> 01:22:20,197
I knew it was not cholera!

826
01:22:20,531 --> 01:22:21,991
Cholera?

827
01:22:22,074 --> 01:22:25,536
He was a quack to say it. I knew it!
Hurry. Hurry.

828
01:22:25,620 --> 01:22:30,416
- Five days I've waited to hear that bell.
- You say cholera? Five days?

829
01:22:31,459 --> 01:22:33,544
Richard! Richard!

830
01:22:34,336 --> 01:22:36,422
Ohh!

831
01:22:37,631 --> 01:22:39,717
Oh, no!

832
01:22:52,354 --> 01:22:53,230
Oh...

833
01:22:53,314 --> 01:22:56,567
How can it be? I heard the bell.

834
01:22:57,443 --> 01:22:59,528
Did you not?

835
01:22:59,904 --> 01:23:01,989
I heard it plain.

836
01:23:02,698 --> 01:23:04,408
The bell rang.

837
01:23:04,491 --> 01:23:08,120
No, missy.
A gust of wind or a tremor on the ground.

838
01:23:09,330 --> 01:23:10,914
I'm sorry.

839
01:23:10,998 --> 01:23:13,083
But I heard it.

840
01:23:13,208 --> 01:23:15,711
<i>(supervisor)
Load this on. Sharp now!</i>

841
01:23:16,211 --> 01:23:17,963
Come along.

842
01:23:18,672 --> 01:23:20,758
Steady. Steady now.

843
01:23:21,467 --> 01:23:23,552
Stand aside there.

844
01:23:24,261 --> 01:23:26,305
Careful.

845
01:23:26,388 --> 01:23:28,473
That's right.

846
01:23:28,682 --> 01:23:32,561
Over here. A little to your right.
Set it down.

847
01:23:32,644 --> 01:23:37,816
- There's more colour to you now.
- Yes, I feel much better now, thank you.

848
01:23:37,899 --> 01:23:39,818
- Goodbye.
- Bye-bye, miss.

849
01:23:39,901 --> 01:23:44,281
- All right for you. I'll be in here with it.
- Rather you than me, mate!

850
01:23:47,451 --> 01:23:49,536
Oh, the stench!

851
01:23:57,836 --> 01:23:59,004
<i>(whistle)</i>

852
01:24:41,629 --> 01:24:44,716
- Can you do it?
- I think so.

853
01:24:44,799 --> 01:24:46,801
It's a long way back there.

854
01:24:46,885 --> 01:24:51,097
Five carriages, 30 feet each,
that's 150 feet altogether.

855
01:24:51,389 --> 01:24:52,807
I'll manage.

856
01:24:52,890 --> 01:24:56,602
- You're not going to get killed, are you?
- Oh, I'd rather not.

857
01:24:57,395 --> 01:24:58,646
Edward!

858
01:24:58,730 --> 01:25:02,817
- Edward Pierce, my dear fellow!
- Damn. Henry Fowler!

859
01:25:02,900 --> 01:25:05,361
He cannot travel in our compartment.

860
01:25:05,445 --> 01:25:07,697
Henry, what a surprise!

861
01:25:07,780 --> 01:25:10,658
- Fancy seeing you! Are you on this train?
- Yes.

862
01:25:11,159 --> 01:25:12,952
As a matter of fact, so am I.

863
01:25:15,329 --> 01:25:20,126
Oh, forgive me.
Miss Bridget Lawson, Mr Henry Fowler.

864
01:25:20,918 --> 01:25:24,672
Miss Lawson is accompanying
her deceased brother but...

865
01:25:24,755 --> 01:25:29,176
..due to the new regulations
she's not permitted in the guard's van.

866
01:25:29,260 --> 01:25:32,263
Therefore she is seeking a compartment.

867
01:25:34,056 --> 01:25:35,933
Well, mine is available.

868
01:25:38,185 --> 01:25:40,730
Henry, you're so kind.

869
01:25:42,982 --> 01:25:44,942
You won't join us, will you?

870
01:25:45,860 --> 01:25:49,488
As a matter of fact,
I've... made other arrangements.

871
01:25:51,782 --> 01:25:53,868
Oh, I see!

872
01:25:54,368 --> 01:25:57,538
- You're quite sure?
- Oh, yes.

873
01:25:57,997 --> 01:26:00,082
You carry on, Henry.

874
01:26:05,462 --> 01:26:07,006
Miss Lawson!

875
01:26:07,089 --> 01:26:10,301
- You're in capable hands.
- You're too kind.

876
01:26:10,384 --> 01:26:12,886
Not at all.

877
01:27:07,274 --> 01:27:10,152
<i>(Agar)
Open up! Open up!</i>

878
01:27:10,235 --> 01:27:12,320
Open up, damn you!

879
01:27:12,404 --> 01:27:13,780
<i>(knocking)</i>

880
01:27:14,114 --> 01:27:15,824
Are you alive, then?

881
01:27:15,907 --> 01:27:18,326
Of course I am, you damnable flat.

882
01:27:18,410 --> 01:27:22,122
- Good God, he's alive!
- Open it! Hurry up. I must be quick!

883
01:27:25,625 --> 01:27:27,502
Lift up!

884
01:27:27,919 --> 01:27:30,005
Oh, mother of God!

885
01:27:30,839 --> 01:27:32,924
Oh, the smell!

886
01:27:34,259 --> 01:27:36,344
The things I must do!

887
01:27:40,682 --> 01:27:44,018
Do you have,
er... many gentlemen friends?

888
01:27:45,103 --> 01:27:50,066
Oh, why sure enough.
Gents are ever so friendly to me, they are.

889
01:27:50,149 --> 01:27:53,403
- Me mum said I was a heartbreaker.
- I'm certain you are.

890
01:27:53,486 --> 01:27:59,033
Me mum was a heartbreaker herself.
Had many a caller, she did.

891
01:27:59,492 --> 01:28:01,494
Many a caller.

892
01:28:01,911 --> 01:28:04,872
And always with some little token.

893
01:28:04,956 --> 01:28:08,334
Me mum says a man loves you,
he shows you proper.

894
01:28:08,418 --> 01:28:11,462
- With some little token.
- Quite so.

895
01:28:12,964 --> 01:28:16,968
If you will permit me, I should be
delighted to give you a "token" myself.

896
01:28:19,345 --> 01:28:23,266
- Cor, you're a bold gent!
- I'm most serious, I assure you.

897
01:28:23,349 --> 01:28:26,644
- What, here on the train?
- Why not?

898
01:28:26,727 --> 01:28:30,398
Have you not heard of
the 50-mile-an-hour club?

899
01:28:30,481 --> 01:28:33,859
I'm told it's beneficial to the circulation.

900
01:28:48,666 --> 01:28:51,752
- But the van's locked from outside.
- It's taken care of.

901
01:28:51,836 --> 01:28:54,463
- How?
- You'll see soon enough.

902
01:28:54,547 --> 01:28:58,634
My friend will come over the top of
the train between Redhill and Ashford.

903
01:28:58,717 --> 01:29:01,887
That's the fastest part of the run!

904
01:29:01,971 --> 01:29:04,056
I suppose it is.

905
01:29:04,640 --> 01:29:08,394
What about all them bridges?
Your friend, mate, he's mad.

906
01:29:36,046 --> 01:29:38,131
<i>(train whistle)</i>

907
01:31:06,344 --> 01:31:08,429
<i>(bell)</i>

908
01:31:18,731 --> 01:31:20,817
<i>(train whistle)</i>

909
01:31:37,625 --> 01:31:39,710
<i>(whistle)</i>

910
01:32:39,436 --> 01:32:41,522
<i>(whistle)</i>

911
01:33:34,115 --> 01:33:36,201
<i>(whistle)</i>

912
01:34:51,275 --> 01:34:53,569
- What's going on?
- Take the rope.

913
01:34:57,698 --> 01:34:59,992
- Is he up there now?
- He is.

914
01:35:00,076 --> 01:35:02,161
He's lucky to be alive.

915
01:35:02,369 --> 01:35:05,790
- Hold on.
- All right.

916
01:35:13,756 --> 01:35:15,841
Now let it go easy.

917
01:35:16,383 --> 01:35:18,469
Go on.

918
01:35:53,545 --> 01:35:55,839
I can't get over the feeling...

919
01:35:56,798 --> 01:35:58,800
You look very familiar.

920
01:35:58,884 --> 01:36:02,804
- Are you sure we've never met?
- Oh, no, sir.

921
01:36:05,349 --> 01:36:07,476
What does your mum do?

922
01:36:07,559 --> 01:36:09,853
Me mum? Er...

923
01:36:10,354 --> 01:36:12,439
She's a seamstress.

924
01:36:13,857 --> 01:36:15,942
An honourable trade.

925
01:36:16,985 --> 01:36:21,907
Me mum's made dresses for Lady
Eversham herself, I'll have you know.

926
01:36:24,576 --> 01:36:27,037
I'm acquainted with Lady Eversham.

927
01:36:28,330 --> 01:36:30,165
Oh.

928
01:36:32,375 --> 01:36:34,461
<i>(whistle)</i>

929
01:37:05,950 --> 01:37:07,952
- All done?
- Done.

930
01:37:08,036 --> 01:37:11,331
Good. We've got less than a minute.

931
01:37:21,174 --> 01:37:23,509
Bloody hell, you look a sight!

932
01:37:23,843 --> 01:37:25,803
I look a sight?

933
01:37:25,887 --> 01:37:28,473
No, but you're all covered in soot.

934
01:37:31,601 --> 01:37:33,561
It's the smoke.

935
01:37:33,644 --> 01:37:37,231
- I haven't brought a change of clothing.
- That's brilliant(!)

936
01:37:37,315 --> 01:37:41,569
What are you going to wear
coming off Folkestone station?

937
01:37:44,030 --> 01:37:45,198
Oh no!

938
01:37:45,406 --> 01:37:47,491
Oh no!

939
01:37:47,783 --> 01:37:53,623
Bloody hell! You paint me green,
make me lie in a coffin with a dead cat...

940
01:37:53,706 --> 01:37:56,083
..and now you strip me bollock-naked. No!

941
01:37:56,167 --> 01:37:58,085
- Shut up.
- Bloody hell!

942
01:37:58,169 --> 01:37:59,920
Let's go!

943
01:38:19,106 --> 01:38:22,943
He'll take the river road
and meet us in Folkestone.

944
01:38:32,369 --> 01:38:37,583
Take hold of the rope.
We'll be through Ashford soon. Pull it.

945
01:38:41,670 --> 01:38:43,756
We'll pass Ashford soon.

946
01:40:13,219 --> 01:40:15,305
<i>(whistle)</i>

947
01:40:52,884 --> 01:40:54,969
<i>(whistle)</i>

948
01:40:57,305 --> 01:40:59,390
Best lock me up.

949
01:41:00,099 --> 01:41:03,978
- Sweet dreams.
- Not bloody likely.

950
01:41:04,770 --> 01:41:06,856
<i>(bell tinkles)</i>

951
01:41:21,620 --> 01:41:26,917
Me mum told me the best gents were the
ones to watch. Full of tricks, they are.

952
01:41:27,626 --> 01:41:34,383
I knew of one caller, wanted me to come
to a room he had, full of whips and such.

953
01:41:35,092 --> 01:41:36,844
- Whips?
- Mm!

954
01:41:36,927 --> 01:41:39,013
Can you imagine!

955
01:41:39,096 --> 01:41:40,848
Mmm.

956
01:41:40,931 --> 01:41:45,102
- Well, me mum, she told me...
- My dear, my dear, my dearest!

957
01:41:46,061 --> 01:41:47,229
Oh!

958
01:41:47,312 --> 01:41:49,398
What a man you are!

959
01:41:51,150 --> 01:41:52,985
What do you take me for?

960
01:41:53,068 --> 01:41:55,028
Aagh!

961
01:41:57,489 --> 01:41:59,575
Ohh!

962
01:42:55,880 --> 01:42:58,425
Impossible woman!

963
01:43:18,236 --> 01:43:19,070
Ha!

964
01:43:19,153 --> 01:43:22,323
Robbery indeed! The very idea!

965
01:43:26,828 --> 01:43:28,913
<i>(cloth rips)</i>

966
01:44:44,822 --> 01:44:46,907
Arrest that man!

967
01:45:17,145 --> 01:45:20,941
The court thanks you for providing us
with so clear an explanation...

968
01:45:21,024 --> 01:45:23,276
..of your manner in committing the crime.

969
01:45:23,694 --> 01:45:27,406
I'm glad to be of help.
The police seemed to be confused.

970
01:45:27,489 --> 01:45:31,201
Do spare us your impoverished
witticisms, Mr Pierce.

971
01:45:31,284 --> 01:45:34,579
Your presence here
attests to their efficiency.

972
01:45:34,663 --> 01:45:37,541
You know, you are a very unusual man.

973
01:45:37,624 --> 01:45:40,252
Mr Pierce, I put it to you directly.

974
01:45:40,961 --> 01:45:44,798
Did you never feel at any time
some sense of impropriety,...

975
01:45:44,881 --> 01:45:47,467
..some recognition of misconduct,...

976
01:45:47,551 --> 01:45:52,973
..some comprehension of unlawful
behaviour, some moral misgivings...

977
01:45:53,431 --> 01:45:57,727
..in the performance of these
various and sundry criminal acts?

978
01:45:57,811 --> 01:46:01,773
- I don't understand the question.
- Evidently not.

979
01:46:02,357 --> 01:46:06,236
Sir, it is a recognised truth
of jurisprudence...

980
01:46:06,319 --> 01:46:08,697
..that laws are created by men...

981
01:46:09,072 --> 01:46:13,034
..and that civilised men,
in a tradition of more than two millennia,...

982
01:46:13,118 --> 01:46:17,956
..agree to abide by these laws
for the common good of all society.

983
01:46:18,414 --> 01:46:20,333
For it is only by the rule of law...

984
01:46:20,416 --> 01:46:26,881
..that any civilisation holds itself above
the promiscuous squalor of barbarism.

985
01:46:27,215 --> 01:46:30,677
Now, on the matter of motive, we ask you:

986
01:46:30,760 --> 01:46:38,476
..why did you conceive, plan and execute
